            "question": {
                "text": "Consider the context-free grammar G below \n\nS \\rightarrow aSb | X \n\nX \\rightarrow aX | Xb| a | b  \n\nWhere S and X are non-terminals, and a and b are \nterminal symbols. The starting non-terminal is S. \n\nWhich one of the following statements is \nCORRECT?",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            },
            "options": [
                {
                    "id": "A",
                    "text": "The language generated by G is (a + b) *",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "B",
                    "text": "The language generated by G is a*(a + b)b*",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "C",
                    "text": "The language generated by G is a*b*(a + b)",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "D",
                    "text": "The language generated by G is not a regualar \nlanguage.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                }
            ],
            "correctAnswer": [
                "B"
            ],
            "solution": {
                "text": "X = a*(a + b)b*  \n\nS = an bn = an a* (a + b) b* bn = a* (a + b) b*",
                "images": [
                    "assets/Theory Of Computation/TOC_Regular_Language_and_Grammar_P23_X1369.png"
                ],
